    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_34327364" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/34327364" />
    <a title="Marshall" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/971451-marshall"><img alt="Marshall" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/34327364?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marshall" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marshall" href="/user/show/971451-marshall">Marshall</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/971451-marshall?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/971451-marshall?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/971451-marshall?shelf=economics">economics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer34327364" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17964570378530278568">This book&apos;s premise is that corporations are pathological, even psychopathic in its pursuit of profit and power. At first, I thought this was just hyperbole, but as I read, I started realizing that any person engaging in the activities this book describes would certainly be described in these terms. And, legally speaking, corporations really are people.<br/><br/>So, at the beginning, I was all set up to be persuaded. Or, more accurately, re-persuaded, since I used to be quite anti-corporate. Back then, I </span>
  <span id="freeText17964570378530278568" style="display:none">This book's premise is that corporations are pathological, even psychopathic in its pursuit of profit and power. At first, I thought this was just hyperbole, but as I read, I started realizing that any person engaging in the activities this book describes would certainly be described in these terms. And, legally speaking, corporations really are people.<br /><br />So, at the beginning, I was all set up to be persuaded. Or, more accurately, re-persuaded, since I used to be quite anti-corporate. Back then, I would have eaten this book up, but these days I'm more skeptical. As the book progresses, it is mildly persuasive, but he overstates his case. At first, it sounded like he just wanted to prevent companies from externalizing their costs (what I like to call "peeing in the pool"), clean up their environmental misdeeds, and treat people fairly. I'm totally on board with that. But then it started sounding like he wants companies to behave more like charities. It started feeling preachy and moralistic, that the profit motive is some kind of sinful impulse that should be eradicated. By the end, he admits that his endgame dream is to socialize all corporations, a la the Postal Service. By that time, I'd gotten off his train several stations back.<br /><br />I don't agree with him that the corporation is some kind of aberrant Frankenstein monster. I think it's an inevitable structure needed for companies to scale. I also believe corporations, for all their misdeeds, also deliver the goods, big time. So there is a trade-off when it comes to governing them. I disagree with him that corporations have made the world worse. There is much less death and suffering than in the past, and this has to do with better economies.<br /><br />That doesn't mean he doesn't make a lot of good points. It is quite the jam we've gotten ourselves into. These companies are enormous, "too big to fail," and they have their hands in all the government cookie jars. For all his arguments in favor of greater regulations, it could also be turned around to show just how lousy the government has been in regulating them. They can make laws, even fine the shit out of them, but obeying laws aren't a moral imperative for them like it is for many human beings. They're just line items on a cash flow statement.<br /><br />Still, what else are we to do? Yes, we need to regulate them, but how? How much? Is there such a thing as bad regulation, and if so, is such regulation actually counter-productive? Besides, if the corporations have the government officials in their pockets, then how can we even expect them to execute the regulations fairly? These are questions he ignores. He not only doesn't answer them, but neglects to raise them. He ends with a little rah-rah pep talk about how great democracy is. It felt empty, considering the complexity of the situation and all the unanswered questions.<br /><br />Socializing the corporations is not the answer. Revoking their charters is not the answer. More regulation is not <i>necessarily</i> the answer. But I admit that it's much easier to say what is not the answer than it is to propose what <i>is</i> the answer. I cannot do that. That's why I read books, and this one did not deliver. Nonetheless, it was worth reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17964570378530278568" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

